<B><A NAME=562>
Management of Alpha Contaminated Wastes   
<BR>
<I>Proceedings Series</I>
</B></A>
<P>
Proceedings of a symposium organized in co-operation with the
CEC, Vienna, 2-6 June 1980. The purpose was to review
technologies and processes in the management of alpha
contaminated wastes and effluents from nuclear facilities, to
identify areas of important progress and to indicate where
further development was needed. Discussions concentrated on
volume reduction techniques, the technology for incoporating the
concentrates into solid forms and the choice of the matrix for
safe interim storage and disposal. Further topics of discussion
were the multi-barrier scheme and the options for disposal of
waste into geological formations. It was demonstrated that the
safe management and disposal of alpha contaminated wastes,
especially wastes containing plutonium, was possible.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> General policies and particular aspects; Alpha
waste management practices; Volume reduction techniques;
Conditioning; Alpha monitoring; Actinides partitioning; Disposal
options.
<P>
STI/PUB/562 (714 pp., 205 figures; 1981)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-020081
<BR>
Price: 1320 Austrian Schillings
<P>
<B><A NAME=258>
Management of Cladding Hulls and Fuel Hardware   
<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 258</I>
</B></A>
<P>
The reprocessing of spent fuel from power reactors based on
chop-leach technology produces a solid waste product of cladding
hulls and other metallic residues. A considerable amount of
research and development work on the treatment and conditioning
of hulls and fuel hardware has been undertaken. However, no final
disposal routes and corresponding repositories have been
established and it was felt timely to review collectively the
various developments in this subject area and to ensure the
dissemination and exchange of the current, most up-to-date
technology in this field.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Introduction; Characterization of spent cladding
hulls and fuel hardware; Treatment and conditioning of hulls and
hardware; Characterization of conditioned waste forms; Storage
and disposal: general considerations; Conclusions and
recommendations; Glossary of some basic terms used in the report.
<P>
