<P>
<B>
Minimization of Radioactive Waste from Nuclear Power Plants and
the Back End of the Nuclear Fuel Cycle
<BR>
<I>Technical Reports Series No. 377</I>
</B>
<P>
Waste management at the back end of the nuclear fuel cycle
comprises the various activities involved in the handling of the
spent fuel once it has left the reactor.  The purpose of the
minimization of radioactive waste is threefold:  (a) to reduce
the risks of radiation exposure of technical personnel as well as
of the public;  (b) to reduce contamination of the environment; 
and (c) to reduce overall costs by reducing the repository space
required for final waste disposal.  Waste minimization has become
a major part of waste management policies.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I>  1. Introduction;  2. Waste minimization
strategy;  3.
Types and quantities of waste generated;  4. Practical waste
minimization achievements;  5. Future trends;  6. Conclusions; 
References;  Appendix A:  Liquid and wet solid waste minimization
techniques in LWRs;  Appendix B:  Dry solid waste minimization
techniques in LWRs;  Appendix C:  General/administrative waste
minimization techniques in LWRs. 
<P>
STI/DOC/010/377 (84 pp., 25 figures;  1995)
<BR>
ISBN 92-0-101195-4
<BR>
Price:  320 Austrian Schillings
