<B>
International Tokamac Reactor:  Phase Two A, Part II
<BR>
<I>Panel Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
This report -- the fourth of a series -- describes work done at
the INTOR workshop which was set up in 1978 to advance the
development of a controlled thermonuclear fusion reactor on a
toxaemic basis. During Phase Two A, Part II, the representatives
from Euratom, Japan, the USA and the USSR held five sessions in
Vienna in 1984 and 1985. Phase Two A, Part II solved certain
critical issues essential to the feasibility and improvement of
the INTOR concept, and the physics and engineering data bases
have also been re-evaluated. On the basis of new information from
critical issues studies and data base assessment and as a result
of additional design scoping studies carried out by the
participants,                
the INTOR design concept was slightly modified; it is, in part,  

             
based on extrapolations of the available data which could be
substantiated by the current generation of large tokamaks before
the                    
project enters the detailed design phase.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> Introduction; Summary; Impurity control; RF
heating and
current drive; Transient electromagnetics; Maintainability;
Technical benefit of partitioning INTOR component design and
fabrication; Physics; Engineering data base assessment; Nuclear;
INTOR concept evolution; Design concept; Operation and test
programme; Administrative appendices;
<P>
