<B>
International Tokamak Reactor -- Phase Two A, Part III
<BR>
<I>Panel Proceedings Series</I>
</B>
<P>
Report of a workshop held in five sessions in Vienna from 1985 to
1987. It is the fifth and final report in the series documenting
activities in the conceptual design of the next generation
tokamak experiment. The activities of the workshop during its
last phase included a definition of the database for fusion, a
study on possible innovations for a toxaemic reactor and a
comparison of different national next generation toxaemic
concepts. The report thus not only proves useful as the final
documentation of eight years of concerted design work by the
world fusion community but is also of great value in providing a
foundation on which the work of INTOR's natural successor, the
International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER), can be
based.
<P>
<I>Contents:</I> (Vol. 1) I. Introduction; II. Summary; III.
Impurity
control; IV. Operational limits and confinement; V. Current drive
and heating; VI. Electromagnetics; VII. Configuration and
maintenance; VIII. Blanket and first wall; IX. Additional physics
issues; X. Additional engineering issues; XI. INTOR related
activities; XII. Conclusions about the INTOR design concept;
Appendix I. Design specifications; Appendix II. Administrative
appendix. (Vol. 2) XIII. Report of IAEA specialists' meeting on
INTOR-like designs; XIV. Comparison of INTOR-like designs;
XV. Operational flexibility of INTOR-like designs; XVI. Systems
analysis of INTOR-like designs.
